campaigns and the impact they had on Alexander, his generals, their troops, and the world. Into the Land of Bones also examines the conflict from the point of view of the local warlords who pushed the invading Greeks to the limits of their endurance-and sometimes beyond, into mania and mutiny. The lively narrative situates the current war in Afghanistan in a broader historical perspective. Holt explains how the three modern superpowers that have invaded Afghanistan-Britain in the nineteenth century, the Soviets in the twentieth, and the United States in the twenty-first-are continuing the struggle that Alexander began centuries ago. That this legacy continues to play itself out today is a testament to the timeliness of Holt's fascinating and original account.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aHistory, Ancient. 4aafghanistan problems. 4aalexander the great. 4aancient bactria. 4aancient greece. 4aancient history. 4aancient warfare. 4aasian history. 4aclassical history. 4aclassical world. 4aground force invasions. 4ahistory of afghanistan. 4ahistory of alexander the great. 4ahistory of war. 4ainvasion of bactria. 4amen at war. 4amiddle east. 4amiddle eastern conflict. 4amilitary actions. 4amilitary history. 4amilitary leaders. 4amilitary strategy. 4amodern afghanistan. 4amodern superpowers. 4awar afghanistan. 4awar in middle east. 4awarfare. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520940314423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520940314.jpg  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles